abstract.0: What if you could benefit from new database quality of services (planned maintenance, unplanned outages, pluggable database relocation, performance, scalability, sharding, and security) without upgrading your applications and drivers? This session presents a new database proxy (CMAN-TDM) that transparently hides planned and unplanned database outages, relocates pluggable databases, protects your database from network fuzzing attacks, shares and reuses database connections at the proxy level  balances loads, caches statements and result sets, prefetches rows, and routes database traffic to right database instance. CMAN-TDM supports all database applications including Java, C, C++, DotNET, Node.js, Python, Ruby, and R.
abstract.1: How does a real-world performance engineer interpret an Automatic Workload Repository or MySQL Enterprise Monitor report? What do they look for, where do they focus their time and effort to get the best returns for the least effort? In this session learn about the top five performance mistakes seen in the field and their impact on system performance, stability, and capacity. If you want to shrink your cloud footprint this session is for you.
abstract.2: This session takes a deep dive into how the Oracle’s data science platform helps enterprise data scientists collaborate on building, training, and deploying models on Oracle Cloud. See the platform's ease of use, project-based workflows, and other features that help data scientists be more productive in helping application developers and business analysts consume more artificial intelligence and machine learning. Learn how the platform integrates with the various IaaS and PaaS offerings in Oracle Cloud to enable powerful and scalable data science workflows.
abstract.3: Who says setting up and operating mission critical databases in the cloud needs to be hard?  In this session, we will explain in detail how using Autonomous Transaction Processing Cloud Service (ATP) will forever changes the approach to database administration, as it enables anyone using cloud services to build a secure, highly available, and elastic database optimized for any workload. We will also demonstrate exactly what you can expect from the service and illustrates how it can simplify your approach to data management and accelerate your transition to the cloud.
abstract.4: Oracle Approvals Management is a highly extensible approvals rule engine that enables organizations to simply and effectively define business rules that determine who must approve a transaction originating within an Oracle application. In this session learn how to configure a simple rule for transaction approval routing by creating approval groups, specifying conditions, and identifying actions to be taken based on those conditions in an Oracle application such as Oracle Payables.
abstract.5: Make your applications run without interruption. Leverage Oracle Database 18c High Availability and Application Continuity features for handling planned and unplanned outages. This session demystifies the Oracle technologies that can be used with language APIs to build resilient applications.  Learn what FAN, DG, TAF, TG, AC, RLB, Oracle RAC, and Oracle Connection Manager’s Traffic Director Mode are and where to use them.  Examples are applicable to C, Python, Node.js, ODP.Net, Java, PHP, and other scripting languages.
abstract.6: In this session learn how to meet your application integration requirements. Oracle Integration Cloud Service includes an intuitive web-based integration designer for point-and-click integration between applications and a rich monitoring dashboard that provides real-time insight into the transactions, and it runs on a mature runtime platform on Oracle Cloud. Oracle Integration Cloud Service addresses SaaS-to-SaaS, and SaaS-to-on-premises integration use cases ranging from simple customer data synchronization across applications to more advanced integration flows. This session introduces the building blocks of Oracle Integration Cloud Service and highlights the value provided by this intuitive and powerful integration platform in the cloud.
abstract.7: In this session join development and product management leaders from Oracle Analytics and get answers to the questions you've always wanted to ask. Hear the plans and understand the current product portfolio. Discuss the capabilities and architecture of Oracle Analytics Cloud. Get ready to drill down in the areas that are important to you and your organization.
abstract.8: In this session learn how to enable the autonomous database features in an Oracle ecosystem to use Oracle Autonomous Health Framework's ORAchk/EXAchk, TFA Collector, and TFAML. Learn to use this consolidated suite of applied machine learning-based tools to run health checks, gather diagnostics, and perform system analysis. These tools autonomously detect and deliver insights and solutions for common problems while streamlining the management of health checks, configuration, capacity utilization, availability, and performance in a "single pane of glass" dashboard. Whether together in Oracle's artificial intelligence for IT operations platform or individually, learn to use these tools to predict, detect, and efficiently resolve problems.
abstract.9: In this session learn about the latest autonomous health features in Oracle Database 18c and coming in Oracle Database 19c. Go through an end-to-end use case to automatically measure and profile an Oracle RAC database workload, deploy it for predictable performance, monitor and manage it for continuous availability, and resolve issues proactively before an outage can occur. This session utilizes Oracle's artificial intelligence for IT operations platform, Oracle Autonomous Health Framework, and its applied machine learning–based technologies to automatically retrieve and store workload performance and profile data, establish baseline performance, detect and prevent or remediate anomalies before availability is lost, and align resources to meet demand while maintaining SLAs.
abstract.10: Understand the tools and techniques available to help you diagnose and troubleshoot Oracle Java Cloud Service issues. Identify the differences in troubleshooting between on-premises and cloud deployments of Oracle WebLogic. In this session Oracle Middleware product experts provide the best practices to improve your experience and get the maximum return on investment with Oracle Java Cloud Service.
abstract.11: This session covers the best practices for performance tuning and optimizing enterprise applications running on JVM 11.  Performance tuning best methodologies and practical tips to solve difficult performance problems for enterprise Java applications are also covered.
abstract.12: Should you refresh your current x86 hardware and keep your workloads on-premises or move them to the cloud instead? In this session hear strategies from Oracle experts on using hybrid solutions to bridge the gap between old and new. Understand how x86 hardware investments today on-premises can help you move to the cloud in the future. Learn about the enhancements to Oracle’s x86 servers that are unique for cloud environments, how to take advantage of those in Oracle Public Cloud, and how you can apply those enhancements to implement a hybrid cloud solution.
abstract.13: Oracle Linux 7 offers the ability to natively implement firewall and load balancer capabilities using no additional software. Combining these capabilities with Oracle Private Cloud Appliance's virtualization using Oracle VM, software defined network, and 40Gb InfiniBand networking delivers a unique opportunity to build complete data center solutions using off-the-shelf software. Attend this session to learn more.
abstract.14: Real-time data is an increasingly popular topic these days. The basic idea is simple: when data in the database changes, any clients viewing the data should see the changes immediately: in real time. Gmail and Twitter are great examples of applications that use real-time data. Users don’t need to refresh the page to see new emails or tweets. Instead, new data is pushed to the clients when it becomes available. In this session learn about some of the tools that make real-time applications easier than ever before, including Node.js and Socket.IO. Of course, the data must be pushed from somewhere, so the session also explores the way that Oracle Database participates in this process.
abstract.15: Enterprises need to rapidly react to the changing requirements of the digital business, without teams of expensive developers. In this session learn how Oracle Visual Builder Cloud Service and Oracle Mobile Cloud deliver an integrated platform to enable the rapid creation of rich, on-device mobile apps with little coding required. See how to extend these mobile apps with mobile-first services such as push, offline, location services, and more, delivered by Oracle Mobile Cloud.
abstract.16: Digital assistant and chatbot support for any language is a worldwide requirement. As of 2009, 6,909 distinct languages were classified, a number that has since grown. For developers, needing to build multilanguage bots/digital assistants with an understanding of natural language in multiple languages can be challenging, especially if the developer does not speak all the languages the chatbot needs to support. In this session explore how Oracle Digital Assistant meets requirements for both multilingual and native natural language processing digital assistants/chatbots with translation services and native language support.
abstract.17: Do you wish Oracle Digital Assistant could ask your enterprise app to tell you more about all the customers you have to visit today, or tell your CRM system that you just closed the ACME opportunity, or ask what your options for medical benefits are for next year? Or do you wish you could automate your contact center by offloading common transactions and questions to a digital assistant? What about leveraging messaging applications such as Facebook Messenger, WeChat, and Slack to engage your customers? In this session see how you can leverage Oracle Digital Assistant to support all this today. And the best part is that you can design the conversational experiences your way, creating tailored conversational user experiences.
abstract.18: In this session learn how to implement and use Security Assertion Markup Language 2.0 (SAML2) security with Oracle WebLogic. Oracle Middleware product experts provide the best practices to configure, diagnose, and troubleshoot SAML2 in Oracle WebLogic.
abstract.19: In this session learn how to set up a simple rule in Oracle E-Business Tax to generate a tax line with a different tax rate or percentage based on the category of the product being purchased or sold (for example food vs. clothes).
abstract.20: In this session learn how to shape enterprise data for more efficient consumption by mobile apps using Oracle Application Express’s RESTFul web services. The solution can be deployed to both cloud and on-premises apps.
abstract.21: The word “integration” has always conjured up a host of different emotions. Beyond stories of implementation delays, online shopping frustrations are actually often caused by integrations not working the way they should. Those days should be over. In this session hear from technologists as they walk through new integration approaches that are less complex, easier to maintain, and foster innovation.
abstract.22: Consolidating databases requires configuring the resource manager to allocate resources such as CPU, SGA, PGA, parallel servers, I/O, flash space, and sessions to each tenant.  How densely should you consolidate?  How should you set minimum and maximum resource allocations?  This session provides an overview of resource manager controls, including new Oracle Database 18c features available, best practices, and methodologies for large-scale cloud deployments.
abstract.23: This four-hour session will provide an overview of workflow approval processes in the Financials Cloud.  Key components of approval management and important approval concepts will be discussed.  Additionally, the session will include instructor demos that will showcase how approvals can be used in General Ledger and Payables.
abstract.24: In this four-hour session learn how to meet your application integration requirements using Oracle  Integration Cloud Service, which includes an intuitive web-based integration designer for point-and-click integration between applications, a rich monitoring dashboard that provides real-time insight into the transactions, and runs on a mature runtime platform on Oracle Cloud. Oracle Integration Cloud Service addresses SaaS-to-SaaS, and SaaS-to-on-premises integration use cases ranging from simple customer data synchronization across applications to more advanced integration flows. This session also introduces the building blocks of Oracle Integration Cloud Service and explores various use cases highlighting the value provided by this intuitive and powerful integration platform.
abstract.25: This four-hour session covers secure coding best practices and guidelines for Java programming. Learn how to keep Java safe and prevent attackers from using common errors to take control. This session also covers real-life examples of secure coding, and explores a set of security features that enterprise cloud application developers can use to prevent their applications from getting hacked. Additional topics covered include authentication, authorization, data integrity, and transport security with programmatic and declarative (annotation and XML) techniques for safeguarding enterprise cloud applications, starting from the client tier and spreading all the way across the web/business tier and data/enterprise information system tiers.
abstract.26: In this four-hour session learn about Oracle Big Data and Oracle Big Data Cloud. See how with Oracle SQL Developer/Oracle SQL Developer Data Modeler you can connect to Hive; use the SQL Worksheet feature to query, create, and alter Hive tables; and automatically generate Oracle Big Data SQL–enabled external tables to access data sources. Learn how Oracle Big Data Cloud used with Apache Spark/Apache Hadoop utilizes Oracle Cloud Infrastructure to deliver a secure, elastic, and integrated platform with Oracle Event Hub Cloud Service (streaming data), Oracle Database (relational data), Oracle Storage Cloud Service (unstructured data), and Oracle NoSQL Database (semistructured) to run a diverse set of big data workloads. See also how to migrate big data workloads into Oracle Big Data Cloud.
abstract.27: In this session take a deep-dive into the latest Oracle Database 18c innovations and learn how they can help your business. Gain insight on Oracle Database big data solutions using database fleet and database sharding, and learn how to use the new portable database snapshots, configure better administrative and data security for a portable database, and how to use the new portable database standby. In addition see how to use Oracle Recovery Manager for recovery of preplugin data and recovering standby database from primary. And discover the new performance enhancements by adding automatic in-memory management and SQL tuning support for standard database clients.
abstract.28: In this four-hour session learn how to use the new onboarding application to engage new hires continuously during the onboarding process. The application uses the enterprise onboarding checklist template to manage the distinct phases of onboarding. All stakeholders, including employees, line managers, and HR specialists involved in the onboarding process can track and manage their tasks effectively in the onboarding application. This session also provides an overview of  the enhancements in the checklist setup functionality. As a result of the enhancements, you can now set the criteria for checklist allocation, completion, task status, task owner, and notifications.
abstract.29: Developers are under increasing  pressure to deliver solutions faster. So often developers are encouraged to just start coding, and are not given time to stop and think about the best solution to a problem. In this session explore what the results of that short-sighted approach can be: failure, delays, and poor performance in your database application implementations. Examine the things done wrong over and over again and see how to avoid making the same mistakes yourself.
abstract.30: RESTful web services are gaining popularity because of better performance on mobile devices. Exposing enterprise data through a RESTful web service, supporting CRUD operations, and maintaining these changing services over time can be complex. RESTFul web services are used by all Oracle software development tools including Oracle JavaScript Extension Toolkit and Oracle Mobile Application Framework, as well as Oracle Mobile Cloud Service, Oracle API Catalog Cloud Service, Oracle Integration Cloud Service, and Oracle SOA Suite Cloud Service to expose and integrate enterprise database data. In this session learn how to declaratively and programmatically implement and maintain data-based RESTful web services with Oracle application development tools using Java and PL/SQL.
abstract.31: This session covers how to use Lambda Expressions design patterns as lightweight design tools to develop robust enterprise applications. Many Lambda Expressions strategies that facilitate the development process are covered. In addition learn how to use parallel streams for optimization, and how to reduce memory footprint and garbage collection with Lambda Expressions.
abstract.32: Take advantage of the free SaaS application training available through Oracle LaunchPad, the free online education portal within Oracle Platinum Services. In this session learn how to use robust filters and search capabilities to get to the training and information you need at the moment you need it. Get a quick tutorial on the subjects available and how to best leverage this and other free education offerings only from Oracle University.
abstract.33: Hardware is cheap, the cloud is here, and resources are all but unlimited. It has been suggested that given this, there is no need to design databases anymore. But a database is not a garbage can you can store anything without understanding what you have. Data is the most valuable property most companies possess, and it should be treated as such. If you want to have good-quality data to base your critical business decisions on, you MUST design your databases. Additionally, now that autonomous databases take care of the boring work, there is time to really design the databases. In this session explore how to design databases directly to the Oracle Cloud using Oracle SQL Developer Data Modeler.
abstract.34: Oracle Database brings unprecedented high availability to .NET applications, eliminating end user service disruption sources from planned and unplanned downtime while requiring few to zero application code changes. Application Continuity enables request replay when a recoverable error makes the database session unavailable. Transaction Guard ensures at-most-once execution after an outage. Oracle planned downtime capabilities ensure end users never experience errors when a database is taken offline. Transparent Application Failover automatically restores session state after a failover. This session discusses how Oracle Data Provider for .NET enables all these capabilities to make user experience seamless during and after an outage.
abstract.35: Encrypting sensitive data has become a must in light of recent mega breaches and ever-expanding compliance regulations such as EU-GDPR. The security of your data depends on how complete the encryption is within database environment and the security and control you have over the encryption keys.  Join this session to learn about innovations in transparent data encryption including online migration from clear-text to encrypted data. Hear about the latest innovations in key management including multimaster high availability architecture for Oracle Key Vault. The session also features real-world customer deployment cases.
abstract.36: Integrating Oracle Fusion Applications such as HCM and ERP within and across the enterprise starts with knowing who your users are and what they can do. Identity and access management makes that possible, often with a click of a button or simple configurations. In this session learn how to use Oracle Identity Cloud Service to integrate Oracle Fusion Applications with your existing SSO infrastructure, ensure the right access for ERP users, protect the application from unauthorized access, and enforce strong authentication. See how to securely extend ERP processes and integrate with enterprise systems while you automate HR processes, reduce errors, and increase productivity.
abstract.37: This session explores how to quickly add a RESTFul interface to existing SOAP-based web service integrations using Oracle SOA Suite and Oracle Service Bus. The solution can be deployed to both cloud and on-premises apps.
abstract.38: In this session learn how to filter, compute, sort, and collect data from big data streams using the Java Streams API.
abstract.39: DevOps has become a common practice in the IT world. Many development teams use DevOps today to reduce turnaround times and get to market faster. Naturally, people in the administrative world are looking at what DevOps can do for them. After all, DevOps is short for Development and Operations. Yet there still seems to be a wider gap to adopting DevOps than there should be. Lots of tasks are still done manually and increase the turnaround time for no good reason. Attend this session to learn more.
abstract.40: In this session learn how to unlock even more performance and increase uptime of Oracle Database by improving your compute infrastructure. Learn from Oracle's database infrastructure experts the top five ways you can use x86 hardware to accelerate Oracle Database for maximum performance. Topics include using the latest flash technologies, the latest Intel processors, and memory acceleration.
abstract.41: Oracle technologies make it easy to include location in analytics, mobile, asset management, and service applications. You can use geo-enrichment to add location tags to business data in databases and data lakes. Built-in SQL, REST, Java, and JavaScript APIs with JSON let you query and analyze information based on addresses, GPS coordinates, coverage areas, territories, or other geographic features. In this session learn how applications were developed using these features and how to use them as part of every database and big data application.
abstract.42: How do you get started using Visual Studio to develop .NET web applications that leverage the power of Oracle Database? This beginner-level session answers that question and introduces Oracle's offerings for .NET programmers, including Oracle Data Provider for .NET (ODP.NET) and Oracle Developer Tools for Visual Studio.  Step-by step-demos show you how to get started with these free products. See how to edit and debug PL/SQL from within Visual Studio and how to execute PL/SQL stored procedures and anonymous blocks from within .NET code.
abstract.43: Do you need global availability and scalability? Then the next generation of Oracle Database sharding is for you. In this session learn how to design geo-replicated transaction processing systems for linear scalability with total fault isolation. Whether you want to use commodity shared-nothing hardware or span data centers worldwide, the latest enhancements to existing capabilities for planned maintenance, high availability, disaster recovery, and self-repair enable best-in-class availability for Oracle Databases of any size on any platform.
abstract.44: In this session gain new insights into your analytics data using graph analysis and database technologies.  See a pipeline used to explore industry-specific datasets and analyze it with the power of graphs. Using retail, telco, and airline datasets, learn how to access database schema, use automated tools to create a graph model, and perform a range of graph analyses to reveal relationships and perform connectivity-based queries. Learn how to use Property Graph Query Language (PGQL) to traverse and query the graph to discover relationships and impacts; invoke PGX graph analytics to discover anomalies, influencers, and communities in data; and visualize the results as a graph in an interactive notebook environment.
abstract.45: In this session learn how to apply policies to an API with Oracle API Platform Cloud Service.
abstract.46: During this deep-dive session learn how to build your own decentralized Blockchain application using Oracle Blockchain Cloud Service and open source and free hyperleger fabric. Get a brief introduction to Oracle Blockchain Cloud Service and see why to choose hyperleger fabric. Learn about the prerequirements, how to build a Blockchain network, joining multiple organization, configuring communication channels, and writing and deploying a Blockchain application.
abstract.47: In this session learn how to combine data from source sites and create a BI application for agile analysis.
abstract.48: In this session learn how to create a user-managed Oracle Data Integration Platform Cloud instance with QuickStart.
abstract.49: In this session learn how to create a web application in a visual application with Oracle Visual Builder Cloud Service.
abstract.50: In this session get a quick look at how Oracle Guided Learning is helping customers with in-context, on-the-job training embedded right in the application.
abstract.51: In this session learn how to develop applications with Oracle SOA Cloud Service.
abstract.52: In this session learn how to create a mobile application in a visual application with Oracle Visual Builder Cloud Service.
abstract.53: In this session learn how to develop simple mobile applications with Oracle Mobile Cloud Service.
abstract.54: In this session learn how to gain visibility into the security of your cloud applications and services to help ensure that your critical data is secure.
abstract.55: In this session learn how to get the value you want from your data with Oracle Analytics Cloud.
abstract.56: In this session get a firsthand look at how Oracle Guided Learning is boosting digital adoption and creating happier users.
abstract.57: In this session learn how to manage a typical workflow with Oracle API Platform Cloud Service.
abstract.58: Oracle Autonomous Database cloud offers a groundbreaking new direction in cloud computing. Migration to Oracle Autonomous Data Warehouse or Oracle  Autonomous Transaction Processing is somewhat different from migrating to a typical platform-as-a-service (PaaS) or infrastructure-as-a-service (IaaS) offering. This session details your options for migrating to Oracle Autonomous Data Warehouse and Oracle Autonomous Transaction Processing, including Oracle Data Pump, SQL*Loader, and the DBMS_CLOUD package. Learn how these migrations work, what user interfaces are available, and how to make the right choice when it comes time to move your database to Oracle Cloud.
abstract.59: In this session learn how to perform basic approval configurations using chatbots.
abstract.60: In this session learn how to simply and quickly prepare your data for analysis with Oracle Business Intelligence Cloud Service.
abstract.61: In this session learn how to easily and quickly provision a compute instance with QuickStart in Oracle Cloud Infrastructure Compute Classic.
abstract.62: In this session learn how to easily and quickly provision an Oracle SOA Cloud Service instance.
abstract.63: In this session get a glimpse into the redesigned, easy-to-use Person Spotlight.
abstract.64: In this session learn how to scale your data warehouse in Oracle Autonomous Data Warehouse.
abstract.65: In this session learn how to send a message from a virtual device to Oracle Internet of Things Cloud Service.
abstract.66: In this session learn how to set up data export and import with Oracle Integration Cloud Service.
abstract.67: In this session learn how to set up patch management in Oracle Java Cloud Service.
abstract.68: In this session learn how to set up revenue profiles in Oracle Financials Cloud.
abstract.69: In this session learn how to  transfer your storage to Oracle Storage and alleviate limitations with local storage.
abstract.70: In this session get an overview of the components and the workflow of Oracle Blockchain Cloud Service.
abstract.71: In this session learn how to maximize your Oracle HCM Cloud experience using the new home page news feed layout.
abstract.72: In this session learn how to use synchronization with the line manager based on HCM position hierarchy.
abstract.73: Microservice Architectures is a very exciting way to develop modern applications. As with any advance, this architecture can impose significant availability and scalability demands on the underlying infrastructure. This session reviews the challenges and shows how Oracle Database features such as multi-tenant, sharding, and the asynchonous messaging capabilities provided by Oracle Database Advanced Queuing, can simplify the development and operation of industrial-strength microservice architectures. This session will also include real-life examples to illustrate how large scale microservice-based applications are constructed.
abstract.74: With unprotected assets in plain sight in databases, no wonder hackers seek to steal sensitive data from databases. Exploiting common vulnerabilities such as unpatched systems, over-privileged accounts, insecure database configurations, stolen passwords, and unencrypted data is a quick place to start. However, knowing the mind of a hacker can better help you strategize and create a blueprint for protecting your database. In this session an Oracle Database security architect (and resident white-hat hacker) first takes you step-by-step into the mind of a cybercriminal adept at exploiting vulnerabilities to access sensitive data stored in databases. Then learn about some of the recent attacks and ways to mitigate them.
abstract.75: Graph analysis employs powerful algorithms to discover relationships in social networks, IoT, big data, data warehouses, and complex transaction data. The low-code, highly automated services for data scientists and developers in Oracle Graph Cloud Service will simplify the creation and management of graphs and allow for powerful graph analysis of database, data warehouse, and data lake content. In this session see an overview and demos of Oracle Graph Cloud Service as well as the other graph technologies for Oracle Cloud, Oracle Database, NoSQL, Spark, and Hadoop including PGX analytics and PGQL property graph query language.
abstract.76: Using way too much electricity and not quite sure where? Tracking usage is a great start, but analyzing data is easiest in a database. Building on the "Watch me make a Watt-watcher" project, this session begins with an overview of the steps and components used to assemble the hardware. Data ingestion to an Oracle Database Cloud is made straight forward with the Python cx_Oracle driver. Get an overview of other cx_Oracle features useful to IoT projects as well, and come away with the tools to track the data in your own projects and hopefully some new ideas. (But no electrical burns!)
abstract.77: Industry analysts report that less than 15 percent of Hadoop applications successfully make it to production. The main reason is Hadoop's notorious complexity, forcing users to spend most of their time keeping their clusters working and not enough time driving real innovation. Serverless changes the game by taking all the burden of installation, maintenance, and upgrade off of your hands while maintaining the flexibility and security that big data applications need. Oracle's serverless Spark service lets you run any Apache Spark application at any scale within seconds, with no cluster to maintain. In this session learn how to run any Spark job, including SQL, Python, R, or streaming; and keep your data safe with Oracle Identity Cloud Service integration.
abstract.78: MOD_PLSQL applications have been doing their job for many years, but it’s time to modernize them to the REST paradigm. This session demonstrates how to do this via Oracle REST Data Services and a case study covering the most common applications of MOD_PLSQL.
abstract.79: In Oracle Cloud, you can view and manage your Oracle Cloud Infrastructure Compute Classic using the REST API, which has been successfully integrated with Oracle Cloud to achieve maximum compatibility with the My Oracle Support interface.  In this session learn how you can create, view, delete, and manage Oracle Database Cloud Service instances using standard HTTP method requests such as DELETE, GET, POST, and PUT. See how to troubleshoot problems with the standard HTTP status codes that are returned in the response header when you call any Oracle Database Cloud Service REST endpoints. With the REST API you can bring standardization, centralization, and simplification to the overall management and lifecycle of the cloud landscape.
abstract.80: Many cities offer comprehensive open data portals, with APIs that provide information on various types of government activities. Making this data publicly available makes governments more accessible and accountable to the communities they serve. Given the right tools to mine and analyze this data, businesses and citizens just might develop new and innovative apps that take full advantage of the data provided. In this session explore a few of the more than 750 public data sets provided by the City of New York and see how anyone can use cloud-based low-code tools such as Oracle Application Express to easily build powerful data analysis tools that tap into data including expenditures, 311 service requests, and demographic and education data.
abstract.81: In this session learn about the new virtualization features of Oracle Solaris 11.4. Discover newly supported features in Oracle Solaris Kernel Zones including support for silicon-secured memory, support for Oracle’s SPARC M7 and SPARC M8 data analytics accelerator coprocessors, and capabilities of using VLANs within Kernel Zones. Learn about multipathing in Oracle VM server for SPARC enhancements that now include support for guest domains using virtual SCSI HBAs within sun4v guest domains. This enables multiple layers of multipathing improving fault tolerance and I/O throughput to SCSI devices.
abstract.82: Oracle Big Data Cloud Service provides an integrated platform for running many types of big data workloads. Cloud infrastructure decisions have an important role in overall application architecture. In this session learn about the performance considerations of the different deployment options available in Oracle’s compute infrastructure, as well as tuning recommendations to help get the best performance from your Spark and Hive workloads in Oracle Big Data Cloud Service.
abstract.83: Oracle Application Express 18.1 focuses on declaratively integrating data sources from remote databases and extending applications running on the cloud via REST. A new Create Application Wizard enables you to add components and features to new and existing applications. Upgrading to the latest Oracle JavaScript Extension Toolkit and jQuery JavaScript libraries will further allow Oracle Application Express to take advantage of new and improved data visualizations and widgets. In this session see those new capabilities and some of the numerous enhancements to Oracle JavaScript Extension Toolkit charts and the interactive grid.
abstract.84: Who says setting up and managing a data warehouse needs to be hard? Come to this session to be introduced to Oracle Autonomous Data Warehouse Cloud, a new service that allows anyone to build a data warehouse. Oracle Autonomous Data Warehouse Cloud provides an elastic and scalable database service optimized for data warehouses. As a fully managed service, it does not require database administration experience to run the system: you simply define your schema, load your data, and start queries. Oracle Autonomous Data Warehouse Cloud includes built-in web interfaces, but also works with all business intelligence and data integration tools. Come learn how this cloud service can simplify your data warehouses and data marts.
abstract.85: In this session learn how Oracle Cloud Infrastructure Ravello Service gives you the ability to rapidly develop and deploy existing data center applications to the public cloud without any modifications to your storage or networking configurations. The solution’s cloud-enabled hypervisor, HVX, lets you easily migrate from an on-premises data center to a public cloud using an intuitive UI to rapidly deploy virtualized VMware and KVM workloads. Retesting costs are significantly reduced as the environment remains exactly as it was in your data center. Use Oracle Cloud Infrastructure Ravello Service’s blueprinting capability to easily create multiple copies of your production applications for development testing, staging, certification or acceptance test.
abstract.86: Every company’s move into the cloud is unique and yet there are common techniques to achieve the best experience for migrating into Oracle Cloud. On-premises and could infrastructure are different and thus different tuning may be needed for the same products. In this session Oracle performance engineers share best tuning practices of various PaaS/IaaS components based on recent customers’ cloud deployments. They also explore how to diagnose and resolve various performance issues with network, storage I/O, object storage, and other compute components.
abstract.87: Oracle Database 12c R1 and Oracle Database 12c R2 both offer some great features that improve upon their predecessors. In this session learn about Oracle Database 12c key feature sets, and Oracle Database 18c. Oracle Database 12c features covered include in-memory options, container databases, and query optimization features. Oracle Database 12c R2 features covered include PDB relocate, lockdown profiles, SGA/PGA for pluggable databases, resource prioritization, and in-memory support on Oracle Active Data Guard. Then get a peek in to the some of the top features of Oracle Database 18c.
abstract.88: In this session learn about the Oracle Database 18c Pluggable Database Snapshot Carousel feature currently available for Oracle Cloud and engineered systems.  The Snapshot Carousel is ideally suited to development environments that typically require multiple copies of databases at different points in time, or to augment a nonmission-critical backup and recovery process. This session provides a complete walk-through on Oracle Cloud.
abstract.89: How do you lift your database to the Oracle Cloud or to Oracle Exadata Cloud at Customer? The Database Development team has the right tool for you: Automated migration, offering different options to migrate, moving your databases and monitoring the process. This session explores the current and planned capabilities of cloud migration tooling, and how you can use it to easily migrate your databases to the Oracle Cloud. Learn how one of the largest retailers in the world moved hundreds of databases to Oracle Database Exadata Cloud Service utilizing Zero Data Loss Recovery Appliance for cross-platform incremental backups. Get the tools and information you need to make your migration a success.
abstract.90: Oracle Exadata is the best platform for running Oracle Databases, offering the highest levels of performance, availability, and scalability. Now in its third year, see what’s new with Oracle Database Exadata Cloud Service. In this session learn how Oracle has combined cloud-based REST services, fast provisioning, elastic compute bursting, and software-defined networking with Exadata’s technical innovations such as Smart Scans, Hybrid Columnar Compression, and IO Resource Manager. This deep dive also showcases live demos of the new features and demonstrates how to use integrated critical database features such as Oracle RAC and Oracle Multitenant.
abstract.91: Interested in learning insider tips and tricks for Oracle Database In-Memory from Oracle product management? If you are, this session is for you. Learn how to implement Oracle Database In-Memory in order to accelerate analytics workloads by orders of magnitude. Learn the basics of setting up Oracle Database In-Memory, and then see the key implementation details and important usage considerations to keep in mind. Explore the necessary additional steps for scaling out Oracle Database In-Memory across Oracle RAC environments. Hear some of the real-world lessons that have been learned from many customer implementations.
abstract.92: Oracle Database In-Memory promises an incredible performance boost for analytics workloads. This session provides a step-by-step guide on when and how you should take advantage of Oracle Database In-Memory. See example use cases and the steps necessary to get started with Oracle Database In-Memory. Learn strategies to identify which objects to populate into memory, how to identify which indexes to drop, and the basics of configuration and data population into the in-memory column store are also covered. Come away with the knowledge necessary to get your first Oracle Database In-Memory–enabled Oracle Database up and running.
abstract.93: This session includes software demonstrations that show how easily Oracle Database integrates directly with Microsoft Active Directory to simplify name resolution, single sign-on, and user and role management. Learn about the new Centrally Managed Users feature that allows you to map Active Directory users and groups directly into Oracle Database users and roles.
abstract.94: Before hackers map out your database users, configuration, data, and security controls to devise their strategy, use new Oracle Database Security Assessment Tool to help discover sensitive personal data, identify database users and their entitlements, and understand the configuration and operational security risks. Attend this session to learn how you can generate Oracle Database Security Assessment Tool reports to create your database security strategy or support GDPR data privacy impact assessments. No prior security experience needed.  And the tool is freely available to all Oracle Database customers.
abstract.95: New technologies such as PCIe NVMe flash open many new possibilities for modern databases. A carefully architected shared NVMe flash system such as Exadata can deliver close to memory performance and scale up to hundreds of terabytes in capacity. This session offers an inside view of how Oracle Exadata embraces flash in its architecture and couples it with software to deliver DRAM-level performance with increased availability and massive capacity. The session explores in detail the unique innovations that Exadata offers to maximize database performance while maintaining transactional consistency and high availability.
abstract.96: Take a plunge into the technical details of Exadata. This session describes what has been done to enhance Exadata and its integrated database architecture, and how to take maximum advantage of some of the new capabilities. This session examines in detail Exadata's hardware and software architecture, database extensions for Exadata, I/O resource management, Exadata’s Smart Scan and Smart Flash Cache features, as well as snapshot and virtualization capabilities.
abstract.97: Oracle Exadata Cloud at Customer continues to attract new customers across the globe and offers a compelling platform for customers that want cloud benefits but can’t move to the public cloud. Oracle Exadata Cloud at Customer uniquely combines the best database technology and Exadata, the most powerful database platform, with the operational simplicity and pay-as-you-grow economics of the cloud in a customer data center. Whether you are an experienced Exadata customer or never used Exadata before, you will benefit from the breadth and depth of this session. Topics covered include deployment, operations, networking, security, backup and recovery, maintenance, and use cases.
abstract.98: In this session learn from Oracle development about the Oracle Maximum Availability Architecture best practices for deploying new Oracle GoldenGate microservices in a clustered environment. This technical session covers integration of the new Oracle GoldenGate microservices with grid infrastructure to automate failover between cluster nodes. Additional requirements for an Oracle Data Guard configuration are also presented.
abstract.99: Do chatbots have a place in your HR department? In this session see how to build a simple chatbot to use with Oracle HCM Cloud using Oracle Mobile Cloud Service and Oracle's rapid development toolkit. This session deconstructs the chatbot to explain how it works and what is happening behind the scenes.
abstract.100: In order to derive value from the Internet of Things, enterprises need to collect data and integrate it with enterprise applications to generate actions that increase the value of the company, its products, and its services. In this session learn how Oracle Internet of Things Cloud Service is a secure and scalable platform to help organizations quickly build and deploy IoT applications, securely connect their IoT-enabled devices and collect data, and then analyze and integrate that data with enterprise applications and processes.
abstract.101: Oracle Linux powers tens of thousands of enterprises around the world on-premises, in the cloud, or as a hybrid. Oracle VM is a key step in delivering applications and cloud services and helps you move your workloads to the cloud. Having Oracle Linux and virtualization skills within a company is the secret to success. Certain skills are universal across infrastructures. A small subset of skills varies, depending on whether you are in the cloud or on-premises. In this session learn some of these key universal and specific skills from Oracle experts, deepening your knowledge and helping to determine the scope of skills you should target for you and your colleagues.
abstract.102: What do Oracle Database listener, dedicated servers, shared servers, pooled servers, Oracle Connection Manager, instance registration, Oracle Data Guard, Oracle Streams, and Oracle Clusterware have in common? Oracle Net Services. It provides a scalable, secure, easy-to-use high-availability network connectivity infrastructure for your Oracle environment, in both on-premises as well as cloud deployment scenarios. This encompasses virtually all areas of the database, so the performance and efficiency of Oracle Net Services has a profound impact on overall database performance and availability. In this session learn best practices for deploying, managing, performance-tuning, and troubleshooting Oracle Net Services directly from experts in Oracle Development.
abstract.103: Oracle Real Application Clusters (Oracle RAC) is synonymous with Oracle Database availability and scalability. New features introduced in Oracle Database 18c as well as improvements to existing features ensure that users can reap the benefits of the latest version of Oracle RAC without manual intervention. In this session get a good understanding of these new features and enhancements. This session also provides an in-depth review of various cluster architectures, including new features that help with a smooth transition to those new architectures. Additionally, learn about the minimal downtime installation, upgrade, and migration paths that Oracle provides.
abstract.104: For more than 20 years, Oracle customers have relied on Oracle Recovery Manager for on-premises backup and recovery. Oracle Recovery Manager in Oracle Database 18c continues these innovations with broader support for multitenant database environments and integration with Oracle Storage Cloud Service Archive Storage. Keep long-term and regulatory compliance backups in the cloud as a low-cost alternative to traditional tape vaulting while maintaining shorter recovery point objective backups on-premises. Attend this technical session to learn about the latest Oracle Recovery Manager backup and recovery strategies, including Zero Data Loss Recovery Appliance. Knowledge gained in this session will enable you to build a full Oracle backup solution, aimed at reducing cost and complexity.
abstract.105: Join the Oracle SuperCluster solutions architect and the Oracle SuperCluster tools development manager in this entertaining and lively session to learn about Oracle's best practices for implementing and running Oracle SuperCluster for maximum availability, serviceability, and operational simplicity. The session also explores the consequences of not following those best practices, with a view to helping customers avoid such situations. In addition, information on the latest Oracle SuperCluster 2.6 best practices is shared.
abstract.106: Development teams are actively looking for new, agile, and efficient ways to expand the breadth, depth, and sophistication of their data analysis. This session explores common patterns and use cases for polymorphic tables, which a new, agile analytical framework designed to support the new types of fast-moving data discovery and big data analytics that are a key part of modern data warehousing. Come and explore how developers can use this agile framework to create efficient, scalable, self-describing, user-defined analytics functions that can greatly simplify data discovery and analysis of big data for report writers, application developers, data analysts, and data scientists.
abstract.107: In this session learn how to make client data highly available by using a container database with or without Oracle Data Guard.
abstract.108: Given the increasing popularity of chatbots and digital assistants, the ability to detect and analyze conversational bottlenecks is crucial as first step toward successful implementation. For instance, it is vital to identify paths in the conversation flow that lead to user abandonment and evaluate reasons for this behavior. While business users require the ability to measure engagement and utilization metrics, developers need to troubleshoot issues to understand what works (or doesn’t) in order to improve accuracy of the chatbot and craft a better user experience as a result. Attend this session to learn how you can accurately gather all of these insights in real time to drive remedial improvements in your digital assistant.
abstract.109: The Meltdown and Spectre vulnerabilities have received huge amounts of press, often with claims of major performance overheads from applying patches to fix the potential exploit. In this session examine the effects on a number of different database workloads and learn how to identify if your system is likely to take a big hit. The session also expands the scope to include other parts of the stack to help identify where the biggest leverage is for performance.
abstract.110: The Real-World Performance team had the opportunity to participate in the design and testing of Oracle’s first autonomous database cloud offering, Oracle Autonomous Data Warehouse Cloud. In this session learn what autonomous performance means and see how to prepare yourself for success with Oracle Autonomous Data Warehouse Cloud. Many of the techniques described are applicable to on-premises data warehouse and can speed the migration to Oracle Autonomous Data Warehouse Cloud.
abstract.111: Oracle Database 12c Release 2 significantly improves the performance of Oracle Database In-Memory features, offering potentially massive improvements in real-time analytics processing and queries. This session takes a deep look at what Oracle Optimizer is actually doing “under the covers” when it makes decisions to process a query against in-memory column store resident and nonresident tables, including improved in-memory joins, leveraging join groups, taking advantage of in-memory expressions, and utilizing in-memory filtering effectively. See real-world performance improvement metrics obtained against an Oracle Database Exadata Express Cloud Service environment that show how best to use these newest Oracle Database In-Memory features.
abstract.112: Oracle Cloud Infrastructure Container Service Classic simplifies the configuration and setup of Kubernetes. This solution provides a comprehensive container and orchestration environment for the delivery of microservices and next-generation application development on Oracle Linux, whether it’s Docker containers or VM-based containers. In this session learn how to build a secure and agile production environment by leveraging Linux containers and Kubernetes orchestration.
abstract.113: As technology changes, companies face a widening gap between the skills they have and the expertise available in the workforce. In this session hear success stories from some of Oracle's customers about how they leveraged Oracle University's complete solution of flexible blended-learning products to enable their workforce and stay competitive.
abstract.114: Migrating on-premises live production databases to the cloud includes challenges such as downtime, application compatibility, performance impact, data security, and choosing the correct cloud vendor and service, to name a few.  Oracle, the database market leader, provides leading-edge capabilities for Database as a Service. In this session hear customer success stories including the strategies they employed to overcome challenges, the methods they used when migrating their databases, and the best practices they adopted.
abstract.115: In this session hear an Oracle University customer panel highlighting the use cases and success stories of enablement strategies that included training at the core of the implementation plan.
abstract.116: Your people are your biggest asset. A quick transformation to the cloud is dependent on having the right skills. In this session hear how Oracle University customers successfully transitioned to the cloud through a focus on digital adoption including the use of guided learning: end-user, on-the job, in-context training layered on top of their Oracle SaaS applications.
abstract.117: This year saw the introduction of Oracle Autonomous Database Cloud, a solution that enables anyone to rapidly build a secure, highly available, and elastic database optimized for any workload. With the introduction of automatic Indexing, Oracle Autonomous Database Cloud will now automatically adapt to changing workloads. In this session discover the motivation behind this new capability and get a first look at it in action. The session also illustrates how it can simplify your approach to application tuning and accelerate new application development.
abstract.118: One-command database upgrade? Yes, the new auto-upgrade tool enables you to upgrade tens, hundreds, and thousands of databases on the command line automatically and unattended. This is a significant step forward in database upgrade technologies. No GUI tools required. Setup done within minutes. In this session the Oracle Database Upgrade Development team demonstrates the tool live on stage. See real-world customer cases and learn how it simplifies keeping hundreds of databases up-to date.
abstract.119: Get instant clarity to improve your business with stunning visual analysis and self-service discovery. Any data, any time, anywhere, easy-to-import to Oracle Analytics Cloud. Data visualization describes the presentation of abstract information in graphical form. Data visualization allows us to spot patterns, trends, and correlations that otherwise might go unnoticed in traditional reports, tables, or spreadsheets. Attend this session to learn more.
abstract.120: In this session learn how the Application Continuity feature, new with Oracle Database 18c, enables all applications—Oracle applications and third-party applications alike—to survive any outage. Manage planned maintenance and database failures with zero brownout from the client’s perspective. Take a deep dive into Application Continuity and see how to best configure your system for continuous availability for your applications.  Hear from Rain and Hail Crop Insurance, which successfully use Application Continuity in production environments, delivering continuous availability with no application changes.
abstract.121: Are you planning on upgrading to Oracle Database 18c? In this session see and learn directly from Oracle's Database Upgrade Development team how an upgrade works—live on stage. Get the latest tips and tricks and best practices from the real world before you kick off your own project. This technical session includes a customer case study involving a large telco and its upgrades of critical systems.
abstract.122: In this session take a quick look at the capabilities of the new Alerts Composer within Oracle HCM Cloud. The Alerts Composer tool provides the ability to send information notification to Oracle HCM Cloud users by email or worklist. See how to quickly create an alert within the Alerts Composer, configure a notification template, and add recipients.
abstract.123: In this session learn about the need for a security schema to manage and secure all user data when using database security policies. This session also explains the privileges needed for an example security user.
abstract.124: In this session learn how to use the seeded "days in period" calculation manager system template in a calculation rule for Oracle Hyperion Financial Management.
abstract.125: In this session learn how to build location analytics and map visualization into applications on the Oracle Cloud using popular developer tools and frameworks with the powerful spatial features of Oracle Database and big data technologies. Go through short examples that let you use sensor feeds, social media data, place names, and GPS coordinates to uncover location patterns, analyze relationships to regions of interest and exclusion zones, track moving objects, and build other useful location-related applications. These typify spatial usage in mainstream cloud development with RAD (REST, Oracle Application Express, Oracle Database), big data (Spark, Hadoop, NoSQL) and popular cloud scripting tools.
abstract.126: .NET Core allows .NET applications to run cross-platform, including Linux. Learn about the new Oracle Data Provider for .NET (ODP.NET) release for .NET Core and beta for Entity Framework Core. These providers fully support standard .NET Core features, such as ASP.NET Core and Configuration API. In this session see demonstrations of developing and deploying these providers on Windows and Linux, including deploying on bare metal and with Docker containers.
abstract.127: Oracle Hyperion Financial Close Management is built for centralized, web-based management of period-end close activities across the extended financial close cycle. In this session learn how to set up and use a simple schedule of financial close tasks in products such as Oracle Hyperion Financial Management, Oracle E-Business Suite, Oracle Financial Data Quality Management, and Oracle’s PeopleSoft Financials. See the dashboarding tools available with the product that allow your financial management team to get a complete view of the status of tasks in the financial close process, including completed tasks, incomplete tasks, and tasks at risk, as well as easily identify bottlenecks in the close process.
abstract.128: In this session learn how to set up and use a supporting reference to capture balance data at a level of granularity that extends beyond the segments of the Accounting flexfield. For example, you may have a single AP liability account, but you would like to analyze the balance in that liability account by the type of supplier: utility supplier, manufacturing vendor, etc. Supporting references allow this additional level of balance analysis without adding segments to your chart of accounts.
abstract.129: DevOps isn't a tool you buy and install, it is paradigm that an organization adopts if its goal is to foster collaboration between development and operations teams. It can help deliver higher-quality applications at a higher velocity while diminishing release deployment stress on the IT department. DevOps is more than a change in your IT org chart. It is a change in culture combined with IT automation and IT monitoring techniques. Ongoing operational costs are drastically lower with automated services, creating predictable outcomes and quality releases. If you’re ready to implement quicker service deployment with predictable outcomes and higher performance, attend this session.
abstract.130: You keep hearing how “low-code” tools are the next big thing in app development and how “citizen developers” are building their own apps using no-code and low-code tools. Oracle Application Express is very much a low-code tool, and even more so with Oracle Application Express 18.1. In this session learn how and why you as an IT professional should engage with these citizen developers to greatly improve productivity, engagement, and for the good of your organization. See how with Oracle Application Express 18.1 you can readily guide these citizen developers to become development stars.
abstract.131: “Why isn’t my query using an index?” is a common question people have when tuning SQL. This session explores the factors that influence the optimizer’s approach to this question. Starting by comparing fetching rows from a database table to finding all the red M&Ms in a packet, attendees then contrast that using an index range scan and a full table scan. Learn about the concepts of blocks and the clustering factor, and hear how these affect the optimizer's calculations. See a demonstration of how these concepts work in practice using real SQL queries. This session is intended for developers who want to learn the basics of how the optimizer chooses between an index range or full table scan and how to speed up their SQL.
abstract.132: In this session learn how Oracle Business Intelligence Cloud Service provides businesses with accessible and meaningful data in a short time frame. This is critical when decision-makers need to move quickly and make well-informed decisions. With Oracle Business Intelligence Cloud Service, you can combine data from diverse sources and quickly create rich, interactive analytical applications and reports. See how the simple user interface of Oracle Business Intelligence Cloud Service enables users to easily load data and create reports in a secure environment in Oracle Cloud.
abstract.133: Zero downtime or the ability to sustain planned and unplanned outages is a key requirement for mission-critical Java applications that use an RDBMS. This session discusses the typical use cases for planned maintenance, i.e., node maintenance, data center maintenance, and multitenant pluggable database relocation. It also covers the use cases for unplanned outages, i.e., network, database instance, and node down. Learn from use cases and solutions using Oracle Database 18c Transparent Application Continuity for Java and the new database proxy Oracle Connection Manager in Traffic Director Mode.

46.globalBio: I started my professional career as a graphic designer and web developer in 2004, but shifted my focus to Fusion Middleware after graduating in 2007. This has helped me become a leader in this emerging technology. Besides investing in IoT, I also co-authored the first Oracle iPaaS book called Implementing Oracle Integration Cloud Service (published in 2017).  My fascination for using the latest technology had led to the research of Blockchain to replace the currently used B2B and B2C integration patterns and tooling. This resulted in me writing a book about Blockchain (across Oracle), which took me about 18 months, which explored the technology behind blockchain, the implications, real-world use-cases and how to implement your own permissioned blockchain.  I’m an frequent speaker at conferences, author / blogger, and participate in OTN ArchBeat Podcasts. In this capacity he is responsible for the development of database features such as the Data Pump, SQL*Loader, External Tables, and Transportable Tablespaces. In addition, Roy runs the global Upgrade Program for the database, coordinating worldwide efforts to make database upgrades faster, easier, and less risky for customers. Roy holds a Bachelor of Science in Computer Science from Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, and a Master of Software Engineering from Carnegie Mellon University.
